title: Anti-surveillance bag (sort of)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This item was designed for the "cutbag" competition - see http://blog.makerbot.com/2011/03/14/twotimes-design-challenge-cardboard-bags/ The object is commentary designed to draw attention to the ways in which our technology is increasingly constructed with "features" beyond our control. The specific "feature" this object draws attention to is the EURion constellation - https://secure.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/wiki/EURion_constellation - an anti-counterfeiting pattern printed onto many modern currencies that is recognized by various pieces of software and colour copiers etc, causing them to refuse to print or copy the e.g. bank note in question. Now, counterfeiting is clearly something that should be discouraged, but I am a bit troubled by the increasingly prevalent idea that if I ask my technology to do something for me, it must first check with e.g. the government to see if it's OK. This is an area of increasing importance to the 3D printing community as well - imagine a world where all 3D printers were legally required to check in with a central repository before every run to make sure your print doesn't infringe someone's IP or security concern. Sounds ridiculous now, but in ten years, there will be people advocating for that... So anyway, by exposing the design both to direct viewing, and by functioning (in a limited way) as a privacy-protection device (presumably photos of you carrying this will not print on certain devices / with certain software) this object will hopefully spark discussion around this issue. Meanwhile, it may also function in a limited way as a digital "opt-out" for collection of your personal image in some contexts. Attributions - inspired by this: http://www.martinbackes.com/new-artwork-pixelhead/
and the EURion constellation was taken from the public-domain image found here: https://secure.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/wiki/File:EURion.svg Update 2011.03.19: Added file body3.pdf - same as original file, but includes the QR code for this page. Update 2011.04.04: Added an image. The laser cutter has temporarily gone away, so in the interim this is a bonsai version cut out by hand, but I did use the posted design files...

Cut out the "body" and "rings" files in constrasting colours, and 2 or more copies of the "strap" file from the carboard of your choice - bristol-board type material might be a good weight to start with. Red lines = cut, blue lines = engrave (for locating rings and folds). For the body, make all folds in the same direction, you will get a box 12" x 12" x 3" with one open edge if you don't scale it. Glue all overlaps. Fold the straps (but don't glue yet) and glue a pair inside the body, one at each end, making sure it goes all the way to the bottom for strength. Then nest the other strap ends as far as necessary to get the ideal strap length for you (could insert a 3rd one here if you want a long strap). After you have all the overlaps worked out, glue the straps in their folded shape. Finally, take the ring cut-outs and glue them on where indicated. I have included 2 alternate body & rings files, one has a single copy of the EURion constellation, the other has 5 (arranged in a meta-constellation). The single version is larger and hence more visible at a distance, the multi-copy might be more effective at triggering some recognition software. As an aside, if you have trouble with the "body" files that you think is caused by the EURion constellation, please post a comment here, I'd be interested to hear how common it is.

title: PowerBot QI Charger Stand / Clamp / Mount / Etc

description.text:
I wanted my powerbot charger to be crazy versatile where I can stand or mount it anywhere. Be it in my living room, office or in the car. Features

  • Has two steel rails that allow you to adjust the height of the charger to suit whatever phone or tablet you have.

  • The base/Stand can also ride on the rails and moving it up and done you can adjust the tilt

  • The stand parts have holes for 1/4 nuts+bolts, I use it give the stand two extra legs to tilt on, but you can probably think of other uses.

  • With two stands you can create a clamp to hold you're phone securely (might need to print a non grove stand and put a stick on material to create a cushion for a tighter grip, can usually find something at an arts & craft store)

  • Has four holes that fit #6 screws to allow you to create and attach custom extensions on the bottom/back, one extension I made allows the charger to be mounted on any 1/4 inch screw, for example tripods. In the photos I use a windshield mount.

    http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00F6SQ1D6/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

    http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00JR5FUQ8/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

  • 6-32 Thumb Screws
    http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B005AYSO18/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

  • For Tripod Extension you need one 1/4 bolt and four 6-32 1/2 inch flat head screws and nuts.

  • For Stand you need two 6-32 nuts and 6-32 thumbscrews.

description.text: Goood

What good is a capo (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:698317) without a guitar? If you've got a big 3D printer and a lot of time, you can print your own! Aside from a few metal bits (frets, tuners, truss rod), all parts are 3D printed in PLA. Please visit http://www.bellinghamfoundry.com/blog/2014/11/3/jeff-kerrs-3d-printed-guitar for a nice writeup done by my local makerspace. And here's a video of me trying to play it: https://youtu.be/fihHMRZgja0 (Photos courtesy of the Bellingham Foundry.)

You'll need a big printer for this - mine is 285 x 285mm  All parts are printed in PLA with 0.2mm layers.  Set the line width to 0.4mm so that the thin walls print properly.   On the neck, use at least 4 perimeters and 35% infill.  
The top and sides print as 3 pieces, the back prints as 3 pieces, and the neck and fretboard both print as 2 pieces.  All body parts and neck parts are glued together with superglue.  (There are ribs on the inside of the body pieces where you can use small binder clips for clamping them together.)  I used gel-type glue and a brush-on accelerator.  Then I went back over the seams with a very thin superglue to get any cracks I missed.  
You'll also need medium fret wire, a set of tuners, a set of bridge pins, and a 1/8" wide bridge, all available from Steward MacDonald.  Use light or extra-light gauge steel strings.  
The neck bolts onto the body using 1/4-20 screws that thread into the heel-rod part of the truss rod assembly (see trussrod.pdf).  The trickiest part (aside from the printing) is fabricating the steel truss rod.

description.text: I lost landing skids of my quadcopter. I decided to attach gimbal in front of the gimbal. So I designed this using other projects here. I made it compatible with Reptile 550 v2 frame. I can't say I'm fully happy with it. Because Dampener balls are not strong enough and gimbal leans forward a little. I used same dampener balls provided with Tarot Gimbal. Although they are not enough to hold the gimbal in front like this. So if you can, get stronger dampeners.  
To hold the motor in place, I drilled a hole on the motor mount and added a screw. You will see 2 holes on the roll motor, use those holes to screw motor in place.

description.text:
Have you ever groped for a knife, grabbing several before finding the one you want? Have you ever considered how clean you knife block truly is?  And have you ever gotten annoyed at how heavy and large your knife block is, and how it gets in the way, taking up precious space?  No longer, as this is a fully washable knife rack with a clear view of all your knives.  This rack can stand up, taking up very little counter space, even leaning forward slightly, mount on a wall or even under a cabinet.  Things could be hung from the bottom when mounted like that, but nothing has yet been designed.  
It can hold 6 knives, four 27-millimeter wide knives and two 37-millimeter wide knives.  The knives can be as thick as 3 millimeters, so it is better for thinner, less sturdy knives, such as bread knives or smaller knives, rather than thicker knives, such as the largest knives in the sets.  However, when mounted under a cabinet, more knives or other things can be placed on top of it, forming a sort of shelf.  It can be washed with relative ease, while it is even easier to decide when to wash it.  The Dual lock, which the link to is in the instructions, is resilient, and will allow the rack to be moved around to different locations, without wearing out like double-sided tape.  
Print it out, and never grumble about your knife block again!

• Print
    DO NOT USE SUPPORTS. In the pictures, some roughness can be seen. These are from supports. Most come off easily, but certain parts are nearly impossible to remove. I even used a rotary tool in the sides. If can print soluble supports, go right ahead. But otherwise, stay clear of the supports. I designed it to bridge, and I have seen the same printer bridge further.

  • Remove supports and raft(if any)
    This is not strictly necessary, but will make the design more aesthetically pleasing, and easier to clean.

  • Attach Dual Lock
    This is the link:
    • http://solutions.3m.com/wps/portal/3M/en_US/Adhesives/Tapes/Products/~/3M-Dual-Lock-Reclosable-Fastener-SJ3870?N=5927706+3294281433&rt=rud When you buy these, get the 1/2 inch(12mm). They can be as wide as 18 millimeters, but after that, they will be wider than the rear supports. Put a set on the rack on the wide sections, and put some on the wall or under a cupboard with the SAME spacing. These will allow you to put the rack where you want it, and allow you to pop it off and move it. After that, nothing is required!

remixed_from.author: HJK14
remixed_from.title: E3D V5 Fan Duct for MendelMax standard X Carriage

description.text: HJK14's fan duct almost worked for my printer (T-MAX 2.0, a Mendel Max 1.5i derivative), but the screws for the pillow blocks were in the way and pushed it down a little, so it wouldn't seat nicely. I added an indentation in the top of that design to allow it to clear the pillow blocks. The pictures show the original 30mm fan that came with my E3D mounted to the duct, and combined, they provide enough cooling to run even higher temp materials (e.g., 250+ degrees) without heat issues in the tube. The pictures were taken while a job was running, so they're not perfect. Update: 2016-01-12 I was teaching myself a new 3D CAD program and I was never quite happy with the airflow through the heat sink, so I thought this would be a good project. I redesigned it from scratch, based loosely on the original design. Not that it really caused any problems, but I believed there was a reasonable amount of backpressure due to the restriction of the conical design of the duct. This new version fits more or less the same, but it has a more open, cylindrical duct the same size as the fan opening instead of a conical one. When mounting it, the rib fits in between the first and second fin of the heatsink.

Orient the part in your slicer with the fan mount down and it should print without issues.   
In that orientation, I unfortunately had some inter-layer cracking issues with ABS in the area that goes around the heat sink near where it attaches to the duct since it's designed to snap onto the E3D v5.  To strengthen that area up, I painted the stress point inside and out with Testors model cement and let it sit for a day to cure.  Painting with acetone or just vapor smoothing the whole thing would probably have worked just as well.
Mine was printed in clear ABS, 0.2mm layers, 0.8mm thick walls, 0.8mm thick top/bottom, with an 0.4mm nozzle.

description.text: This will press your dough for homemade tacos, tortillas or the chips for chips and salsa. I wanted to make this for myself and noticed this contest. The pictures are from a proof of concept print, printed on the lowest quality settings. The files ending with "V2" are version 2 of the project. I did not print or test the second version. The first version works fine but needs a little cleanup at the hinges. There are small adjustments to the V2 files. There is more room around the hinges in the base unit, and instead of a round handle the rectangle is used for the entire handle. The longer square handle is easier to press. I do not have a 3D printer, ​I would like to thank the Fayetteville Free Library for the use of their 3D printers. ​http://www.fflib.org/make/fab-lab. When filling your tacos be sure to use http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:704856 which is also entered in the Countertop Challenge contest.

The base is the bottom section, the top goes on the lower hinge, the handle is on the top hinge.
I used supports for the top and the handle. The base did not need supports. I used rafts for all items because I always use rafts. Because of the pressure used to press you might want to use more fill and more shells. The lowest quality settings on a Makerbot Replicator 2 worked fine for this proof of concept print. I think the print could be a little larger but it might not fit on your print bed. On the Replicator 2 you can try scaling all items to 110%. I would also look into getting food grade enamel paint and give the press two coats. I have two versions of the handle and the base. The second version has V2 at the end of the file name. You need to print out one or the other. Version 2 is untested.
(note: after testing version one I would recommend printing version 2 of the handle. I am keeping it active because of the contest)

description.text: 3 cosas pedorras que hice y/o modifiqué.

Plates for a 3dprinter of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2415 . They are done in openscad and require the original files from the Mini servo gripper. There are currently two plates: one for geared parts, another for the rest of the parts. This is so you can print the gears at better quality and to avoid possible ooze making them not fit properly. The original versions are just a plate directly made from the original files. There is also gripper_plate_v2 which contains tweaks for 3d printing. Namely it merges both 4mm tall arms into a single 8mm tall one and the base is modified to fit an HXT900 servo and merges both servo plates. This decreases the parts needed and helps
simplify assembly. A video of it in action: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-3I8lXD45wI Files:
  • gripper_plate.scad: Openscad code for the original plate.
  • gripper_plate_gears.scad: Openscad code for the gear plate.
  • gripper_plate.stl: Rendered model of the original plate.
  • gripper_plate_gears.stl: Rendered model of the gear plate.
  • gripper_plate_v2.scad: Openscad code for the modified plate.
  • gripper_plate_v2.stl: Rendered model of the modified plate.
  • Gripperservoplate_v2.stl: The new servo holder part (in gripper_plate_v2).
    • Total weight assembled with Natural PLA: 53 grams (including servos and screws).

Print gripper_plate_v2 and gripper_plate_gears then assemble.
I'd recommend filing the gears and adjusting them with a cutter so they fit properly. It's pretty important so the friction and forces don't break the servos which is pretty easy to do (broke one already, luckily had spare gears).

title: Replicator Mini - Build plate support tougher version

description.text:
This is not my idea idea, I just adapted it to my liking and...
Well, share with people like he was kind enough to do so before me. Remix of: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:615358
By: muzz64

The original design was good, a bit wide in the locking part but good. Until I found that on my machine the support would eventually slip from side to side and doesn't support the very end of the build plate.  
If I was going to put a support underneath, I wanted it as tough as I can while keeping it cost efficient, easy to print and lightweight.

It's wider, longer and thicker (you already hear that from someone else didn't you...).  
Being almost the same size in lengh (minus 0.75mm) as the under part of the stock build plate, it will limit the movement from side to side (X axis).  
As the width is also close to the build plate (minus 2 to 3 mm) it will support the whole plate (Z axis).  
To prevent the support from moving around, there's 3 pin that fit right in the printer's build plate support, put it, push a bit and it's locked!  
So it's pretty much the biggest support plate you can do for the Replicator Mini.  
Honeycomb pattern underneath is here for strengh while maintaining the weight low.
Some model are not there, you can find more here: https://www.cgtrader.com/M600

Build space required: 110x110mm  
The print you see is 200 microns with 50% infill.  
It's 46.23gr and took me a little less than 4 hours.  
You can go with thicker layer (300) and lighter infill, it won't affect much in my opinion. Don't go 10% ;)

description.text:
This is version 0.3 of the UltiRouter mini mill. It fits the form factor of the ultimaker, so if you already have an UltiMaker 3d printer, you can stack them.
The last version was still too complicated to assemble with too many tabs per side. This version only has one or two per side, making it much easier to go together. The first set that I cut out was assembled before I could make any pictures.

The dxf and rhino files have layers in them, numbered 1 to 8 (and some more unnumbered ones). There is already an offset in there for a 3 and 5 mm flat tip bit, so use that to cut out each layer according to the instructions in the layers (depth, size etc). The last layer/operation cuts out all parts, so if you have no other way of fixing your parts to the bed (vacuum bed, chewing gum) you should fix each part with a least two screws in the small 3mm holes. The front frame has no screw hole for aesthetic reasons, so clamp/hold this to the bed in some other way.

Print and Play!
.
From the Wikipedia article:
.
The Tower of Hanoi (also called the Tower of Brahma or Lucas' Tower, and sometimes pluralised) is a mathematical game or puzzle. It consists of three rods, and a number of disks of different sizes which can slide onto any rod. The puzzle starts with the disks in a neat stack in ascending order of size on one rod, the smallest at the top, thus making a conical shape.
.
The objective of the puzzle is to move the entire stack to another rod, obeying the following rules:
  • Only one disk may be moved at a time.
  • Each move consists of taking the upper disk from one of the rods and sliding it onto another rod, on top of the other disks that may already be present on that rod.
  • No disk may be placed on top of a smaller disk.
    • With three disks, the puzzle can be solved in seven moves.
